<br>
If I can find it again I will give credit to the group that came up with this idea... The one biggest decision made at their very first Meetup was everyone made a commitment to bring along one other person to the very next Meetup. Just imagine the growth if everyone gave this pledge. It could be just the thing we need to get more people involved in Conservativism.<br>
<br>
What say all of you?<br>
<br>
David <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mdlestat>mdlestat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(12/28/03 9:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Meetup growth proposal.</span><hr size=1> Growth is one of the most important goals to work for, absolutely! And you're right--it really IS as easy as bringing just ONE new person in--with that kind of multiplication of bodies (if you actually repeated it every month), we'd each have groups numbering in the hundreds relatively quickly...<br>
That said, I think word-of-mouth about the actual content of the meetings themselves will dictate as much, if not more, what ultimate attendance will be. Having fun, interesting meetups (vs. dull, disoriented, and unorganized ones) will get us more members long-term than the most dedicated recruitment drive. Methinks. <br>
